		   "state" : "open",
		   "body" : "*(I blabber, scroll down a bit if you want to see some issues and suggestions)*\r\n\r\n*Disclamer: I'm not a long-time DuckDuckHack contributer, I have a lot to learn and I'm not as well versed in Perl as many of you will be (I mostly write Haskell), so please, feel free to scream (or politely shout) at me if I've made some horrible error in the way things are supposed to work.*\r\n\r\n***Begin***\r\n\r\nI recently wrote a small fix for the Calculator Goodie, but had a bit of pain finding where exactly the issue was due to the verbosity of the goodie. @moollaza informed me that the Calculator is one of the oldest IAs, so through updates it is getting a bit messy.\r\n\r\nWhils't doing my fix, I noticed some odities in the way the goodie was written, and since then I have looked further in to it and come up with many suggestions for improvements.\r\n\r\n**I propose that the Calculator IA be re-written**\r\n\r\n`Calculator.pm` is approximately 190 sloc, with roughly 120 tests - not huge. I believe that a re-write would allow this code-base to be reduced significantly, whilst making the goodie more robust and potentially add more features.\r\n\r\nI am aware that there are other powerful calculator implementations, such as [this]\r\n(https://duck.co/ia/view/symbolab) spice, and [this](https://github.com/duckduckgo/zeroclickinfo-spice/pull/1727) promising GUI implementation; but Perl is a very powerful language, and a **lot** of people have invested in it - resulting in [some powerful math libraries](https://metacpan.org/search?q=Math).\r\n\r\nThe current Calculator implementation is very focused on using regular expressions to attempt to normalize user queries (`s/ (\\d+?)E(-?\\d+)([^\\d]|\\b) /\\($1 * 10**$2\\)$3/ixg` `2e3` anyone?) many of which are unnecessary.\r\n\r\nI propose that a 'new' Calculator Goodie be made, with the intent of giving the user as much mathematical power as possible, whilst keeping the codebase clean and well documented, and delegating hard-work to libraries such as `Math::BigFloat` and `Math::BigInt`.\r\n\r\n## Some current issues\r\n\r\n*I would include screenshots... but think of the scrolling...*\r\n\r\n1. *The code.*\r\nIt ain't pretty... And I'm pretty sure a lot of it doesn't need to be there. A good re-write would naturally fix this through careful planning and constant refactoring.\r\n2. *Queries.* Some queries **just don't work**. Take for example, `e` (`* 10 to a power`). The query `1 + 3e8` works fine, but `3e8` on its own? Nope. This could be taken as erring on the side of safety, who knows what `3e8` could really be referring to (things like `2e3` and `2e4` already come up with IA results)? But prefixing the query with `calculate` doesn't fix this, even though the user is being *very* explicit. This should change.\r\n3. *Premature delegation.* The [spice](https://duck.co/ia/view/symbolab) mentioned earlier has its uses, but they lie with more complex mathematics such as calculus. The current Goodie is relying on it too much. As an example, the query `calculate 1 + 2e`. This isn't a complicated computation, and should be handled directly by the Goodie, rather than having to send out an API call (as it currently does). Besides, the SymboLab call is (by default, don't know if you can change this) only giving back 5 decimal digits! Perl supports 40 (ish) ***cached*** digits of `e` out-of-the-box with `Math::BigFloat->bexp(1)`.\r\n\r\nI have many other issues and things that could be improved noted down, but I'll stop here for now, hopefully I've convinced you.\r\n\r\nIf you agree - I'll be happy to put time into this, I think this is a very fundamental Goodie (too much maths?).\r\n\r\n## TL;DR\r\n\r\n*(you lazy... - that took me ages to write!)*\r\n\r\n**I think the calculator needs re-writing.**\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n",
