		   "state" : "closed",
		   "body" : "Well, they deserve it.\r\n\r\n## Changes\r\n\r\n### Triggering\r\n\r\n#### General Triggering\r\n\r\n**The current State**\r\n\r\nAt the moment, we have many cheat sheets each designed to convey different information. Some provide language references, others keyboard shortcuts, as well as many others.\r\n\r\nCurrently, there is no discrimination when it comes to triggering - language cheat sheets will triggers on `keyboard shortcuts` just as those *intended* to convey keyboard shortcuts will. This is not ideal as it causes a lot of over-triggering (and potentially confusion!). I don't know about you, but typing in `jQuery key bindings` should not cause a language reference to appear!\r\n\r\n**The Fix**\r\n\r\nTo fix this I've changed the way triggers work by defining categories that each have triggers associated with them; `math` triggering on `formulae`, `keyboard` triggering on `shortcuts` etc...\r\n\r\nInitially the `template_type` of the cheat sheet will cause a default category to be assigned - thus the `keyboard` template type gets assigned the triggers for `keyboard`. Additional categories may be specified in an `additional_categories` attribute when it makes sense to trigger from another category.\r\n\r\n#### Custom Triggers\r\n\r\nI've seen mentions of \"Oh, can I get my cheat sheet to trigger on X?\" mentioned around, and often the answer is either \"Use an alias\" or \"No\".\r\n\r\nThis feature aims to fix this by providing a means of specifying additional triggers for cheat sheets.\r\n\r\nThe supported triggers are `start`, `end`, `any`, and `startend. By default the name (or an alias) of the cheat sheet is still required to trigger, by this may be turned off.\r\n\r\n**Example**\r\n\r\nSay we have a cheat sheet, `historical artifacts`, that displays some notable artifacts from ancient history.\r\n\r\nObviously the category for this cheat sheet should be `reference`. Now the cheat sheet will trigger on `historical artifacts cheat sheet`, `historical artifacts reference` etc...\r\n\r\nMaybe we want to have it trigger on `ancient artifacts`? No problem, we just add the `historical artifacts` alias.\r\n\r\nBut hang on... Now we want it to trigger on `list of historical artifacts` and `list of ancient artifacts`, but none of the existing categories allow this!\r\n\r\n~~Now the custom triggers come into play, by specifying:~~\r\n\r\n```JavaScript\r\n\"triggers\": {\r\n    \"start\": \"list of\"\r\n}\r\n```\r\n~~in the attributes for the cheat sheet, the desired behavior can now be achieved!~~\r\n\r\nThe new method of implementation is through the `triggers.json` file, as discussed in the comments (I might add that here).\r\n\r\n## To-Do\r\n\r\n- [x] Allow specifying custom triggers in JSON\r\n- [x] Allow specifying multiple categories\r\n- [x] Fix all the lovely `$key` warnings (need to PR `DuckDuckGo`)\r\n\r\n---\r\n[IA Page](https://duck.co/ia/view/cheat_sheets)\r\n\r\n",
